          <p class="wdys-faq-a">You cannot see both interpretations of an ambiguous figure at the same time because the visual cortex operates as a single-winner competitive network. When two different visual hypotheses compete, reciprocal inhibitory connections between specialized neuron groups in the visual cortex actively suppress the weaker signal. When one hypothesis is selected as the conscious "figure," the other is relegated to the "ground." This winner-take-all architecture is an evolutionary advantage: in the wild, the brain must make rapid, unambiguous decisions for survival (such as identifying a predator). The constant switching between interpretations occurs because the active neural population tires over time, allowing the suppressed hypothesis to rise and dominate.</p>
